Planetterp: Analyzing Professors' Ratings and their Salaries¶

By: Anna Phung¶

Introduction¶

In 2017, students from the University of Maryland (UMD) published a website called Planetterp.com which serves as a platform for UMD students to post their personal reviews of instructors online. When choosing classes, it is useful resource for those who are signing up for classes and would like to understand if the professor would be a right fit for them. The website provides a variety of data about classes and professors. For each professor, students can see their averaged rating out of 5 stars, written reviews, grade distributions, as well as what other classes are taught by the individual.

It is important to note that these reviews are mostly anonymous and reflects a student's personal opinions. There is no objective definition of a "good" professor, or for someone who deserves a 5-star rating. These reviews may be biased. Nevertheless, they provide a window into the general student body's opinions on UMD's instructors. It is important to understand how these ratings are distributed and what factors could potentially be associated with them. Is there differences in professor ratings across departments? Is there a correlation between a professor's salary and their rating? This analysis will serve to answer these questions and more. The intention of this analysis is to determine if there are any unusual disparities among professors and departments, and to act as a stepping stone to potentially guide UMD's protocol in the future. Any findings can be used as basis to convince UMD to change hiring and salary standards to provide the best experience for students.

Extracting and Cleaning the Data¶

Planetterp has a public API accesible via https://planetterp.com/api/v1. Visit this page for further documentation on how to use the API. Using the requests python package, a request was made to the /professors endpoint to retrieve data about UMD instructors. The API returns a maximum of 100 entries at a time in json format in alphabetical order, so it was repeatedly called until all professors were returned.

The json files were all compiled into a dataframe represented through the pandas library. There are 6 columns:

  • courses - A list of courses taught by the professor/teaching assistant (TA)
  • average_rating - A numerical rating out of 5, calculated by averaging all the reviews by students if any exist
  • type - A string to categorize individuals as either 'professor' or 'ta'
  • reviews - A list of all students' reviews
  • name - The name of the professor/TA
  • slug - The unique identifier used by Planetterp (typically the last name)

The data has to be cleaned up before further analysis. The data contains information on both professors and teaching assistants (TA), but for the purpose of this study, we will only focus on professors. Thus, TAs were removed from the dataframe. The study also largely focuses on a professor's ratings/reviews, so if a professor has none, then they are removed from the dataframe.

The 'courses' column extracted straight from Planetterp's API is not always accurate because it was compiled by pulling information from UMD's Schedule of Courses. It does not contain information about new courses an instructor may be teaching the current semester. Thus, if any of the new courses are mentioned in their reviews, that course is added to their existing 'courses' column.

# Function to extract all the professor review data on planetterp.com
def get_planetterp_df():
  df = pd.DataFrame()

  # Makes initial request
  r = requests.get('https://planetterp.com/api/v1/professors?limit=100&offset=0&reviews=true')
  offset = 0
  # Iteratively get the next 100 records of data
  while len(r.json()) != 0:
    df = pd.concat([df, pd.DataFrame(r.json())])
    offset += 100
    r = requests.get(f'https://planetterp.com/api/v1/professors?limit=100&offset={offset}&reviews=true')
  df = df[df.type == 'professor']
  df = df.dropna()

  # Get all the courses from the reviews
  def get_courses(x):
    list = []
    for entry in x:
      list.append(entry.get('course'))
    return list

  # Merge together past courses and recent courses where professors have reviews on
  df['courses'] = (df['courses'] + df.reviews.apply(get_courses)).apply(set).apply(list)
  df.name = df.name.str.lower()
  return df

In this study, we would like to investigate if there is any patterns in professors' salaries, and to get this data, we can use the Diamondback (DBK). The DBK is a newspaper lead by UMD students, and every year, they recieve data from the school reporting the salaries of school faculty. The newspaper has a publically available API at https://api.dbknews.com/ where the salary data is available at the salary endpoint. Documentation of how to use this API is found here. Unfortunately, the data is split into pages, where each page only holds 10 entries of data, and there are 1000+ pages per year. In order to not overload the servers and unintentionally initiate a DOS attack, a random wait time between 5 and 10 seconds is integrated between each request. Read more about common pratices to web scrape without disrupting service here.

In [ ]:
# Make a pandas dataframe containing all the professors' salary data for that year
def get_dbk_df(year):
  df_salary = []

  # Form the initial request
  r = requests.get(f'https://api.dbknews.com/salary/year/{year}?search=&sortby=salary&order=desc&page=1')
  page = 1

  # Iteratively getting each page for the year (while waiting 5-10 seconds between each call)
  while len(r.json()['data']) != 0:
    df_salary.extend(r.json()['data'])
    page += 1
    r = requests.get(f'https://api.dbknews.com/salary/year/{year}?search=&sortby=salary&order=desc&page={page}')
    time.sleep(random.randint(5,10))
  
  # Turn data into a pandas dataframe
  df_salary = pd.DataFrame(df_salary)

  # Function to format the name into 'firstname lastname' (all lowercase)
  def reformat_name(x):
    reg = re.match("^(.+),\s([^\s]+)", x)
    return (reg.groups()[1] + " " + reg.groups()[0]).lower()

  df_salary['Division'] = df_salary['Division'].str.replace("\n", " ")  # Clean data of any '\n'
  df_salary['Department'] = df_salary['Department'].str.replace("\n", " ")
  df_salary['Title'] = df_salary['Title'].str.replace("\n", " ")
  df_salary['Employee'] = df_salary['Employee'].apply(reformat_name)  # Reformat names
  df_salary['Salary'] = df_salary['Salary'].apply(lambda x: float(x[1:].replace(",","")))   # Turn salary into numbers

  # Save the data frame as a csv for convenience and speed
  df_salary.to_csv(f'/content/drive/My Drive/CMSC320/Data/dbk_salary_{year}.csv')
  return df_salary

# Takes in a list of objects and returns only the review portion of it
def extract_reviews(row):
    list = []
    for entry in ast.literal_eval(row.reviews):
      list.append(entry.get('review'))
    return len(list)

# Extracts the number of reviews for each professor

Creating new data frames¶

With this study, we are hoping to eventually analyze the professor ratings and salaries with respect with each other, so it would be much easier to merge the two data frames together. Saving this as a separate data frame will save some time from constantly doing look-ups.

Merging the two data frames would be a simple procedure if only the professors at UMD never changed, but that is not the case. Professors come and go every year, thus there are some professors who are present in the planetterp.com data frame, but are only listed in the DBK salary report in previous years depending on when they taught at UMD.

To resolve this, I created a function that looks back at time to find records of each professor in the DBK salary reports. It only looks back as far as it needs to so it will only pull the most recent records of the professor. These records would then be added to the corresponding entry in the planetterp data frame.

In [ ]:
# Add the years so we know what year the salary was pulled from
for i in range(len(dbk_salaries)):
  dbk_salaries[i]['year'] = 2013+i

# Matches a professor to their most recent salary information
def get_most_recent_info(row):
  name = row['name']
  salary = np.NaN     # default salary value is NaN
  index = len(dbk_salaries) - 1
  year = np.NaN
  while salary is np.NaN and index >= 0:    # Loops from 2022 to 2013 salary data until an entry with their name is found
    match = dbk_salaries[index][dbk_salaries[index]['Employee'] == name]
    if len(match.index) >0:
      salary = match.iloc[0]['Salary']
      year = 2013+index
      return salary, year, match.iloc[0]['Department'], match.iloc[0]['Title']      # Returns their data if match is found
    index -= 1
  return salary, year, np.NaN, np.NaN   # Otherwise, return default values of NaN

# Creates a new data frame containing professors' ratings along with their most recent salary, department, and titles
merged_df = df.copy()
merged_df[['salary', 'salary_year', 'department', 'title']] = df.apply(get_most_recent_info, axis=1, result_type='expand')

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We now have the data in a easily digestible format for analysis. Before doing any statistical tests, we should explore our data to see if we can find any interesting shapes and/or patterns. This is an important step to understanding our data and gaining insight on what questions should be asked. Knowing the shape of our data will also aid us in doing hypothetical tests. Let's first explore the professors ratings.

Planetterp.com Data¶

What does the distribution of average ratings look like?¶

We should first look at a plot of all the ratings on planetterp.com. In the graph below, the x axis represents a professor's average rating. It ranges from 1 to 5, 1 being the worst and 5 being the best for a professor. The y axis represents the number of individuals who fall within each bin.

In [ ]:
sns.histplot(data=df, x='average_rating')
plt.title("Distribution of all Ratings on Planetterp.com")
plt.xlabel("Average Rating")
plt.text(5.5, 550, f'Median: {np.median(df["average_rating"])}, iqr = {iqr(df["average_rating"])}', fontsize = 12)
Out[ ]:
Text(5.5, 550, 'Median: 4.1, iqr = 2.0')

The median rating is 4.1, with an interquartile range of 2 stars. This average rating distribution is extremely left-skewed, with a large majority of instructors getting a score between 4.75 and 5.0.

Note that this graph was created by plotting the data of everyone listed on plannetterp.com with reviews. It is important to know that anyone who has taught/lead a class may find their name on this website, including lecturers, coordinators, and TAs. Not everyone holds the same level of responsibilities, so to control for this, we will filter strictly by those with the 'Professor' title.

In [ ]:
# Looks for people with 'Professor' as their title (or 'Prof' for short)
def prof_filter(title):
  if (type(title) != float):
    return 'Prof' in title or 'Professor' in title
  return False
merged_df_prof = merged_df[merged_df['title'].apply(prof_filter)]   # Creates a new data frame containing only professors

# Graphs the ratings of only professors
sns.histplot(data=merged_df_prof, x='average_rating')
plt.title("Distribution of Professors' Ratings on Planetterp.com")
plt.xlabel("Average Rating")

Out[ ]:
Text(5.5, 65, 'Median: 3.84, iqr = 1.63395')

The distribution is now much more evenly distributed along the range of possible all possible ratings. The median is now 3.84, and the interquartile range was lowered to 1.63. Higher ratings are still more common than lower ratings, but now there is not a disproporationately high number of 5 star ratings.

Notice that there are peaks at each whole number interval (ie. 1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.). This is because many professors may have only one review on their profile, leading to the average being a whole number. What would the distribution look like if we were to look at professors with more than 1 review? 2 reviews? 5 reviews?

Out[ ]:
Text(5.5, 35, 'Median: 3.6667, iqr = 1.6060000000000003')

In the above plot, we have several graphs in a row showing the distribution of average ratings among professors with more and more reviews. In the first plot, we are graphing the distribution of ratings among professors with more than 1 review, while the last plot is doing the same but among professors with more than 8 reviews. As the number of reviews increase, you can see that the distributions are becoming more and more normal. The peaks also disappear. Towards the end, the distributions start looking more symmetrical, and the center of the data is moving more towards 3.

There can be many speculations as to why this could be. Perhaps there are a lot of 5 star professors because there are only a handful of students who are passionate enough to write a review for new professors, especially if they had a very positive experience. This is also known as selection bias, which occurs if respondants have a choice in giving away their data. This could potentially be the case here because not every student is obliged to give their opinion. Another possible explanation is that some professors may have a teaching style that people either agree or disagree with. These professors may be a bit controversial, conjuring up mixed reviews in large sums.

How do ratings differ among different departments?¶

We know what the overall distribution looks like, but what if it were separated by departments? Do departments have different distributions of professor's ratings? Are there departments that tend to have higher ratings? Are there departments with very low ratings? This can help shed some light on which departments need some improvment in regards to teaching students.

for i, v in enumerate(medians):

for i, v in enumerate(sizes):

Hypothesis Tests¶

After analyzing the data, we are left with a lot of questions with not many answers. Planetterp.com data is incomplete at best; there are many professors who do not have reviews, and of the ones that do have reviews, many do not have enough to reliably gauge the quality of their teaching style. While I did pull all the data that planetterp.com has to offer, what I really have is simply a sample of student's opinions. In order to answer any questions with a quantifiable amount of certainty, I have to rely on hypothesis tests. Hypothesis tests enable us to calculate how confident we can be to make certain statements about the population through only using sample data. The challenge is in determining how much of the variance we are seeing in the sample is attributable to random sampling error versus actual differences in the population. That is why it is essential to run a statistical test whenever trying to draw a conclusion from the planetterp.com data.

In contrast, the salary and department data I pulled from The Diamondback holds the information of all faculty at UMD for the particular year. In other words, we are dealing directly with population data, not sample data. There is no need to run hypotheses tests to make statements about the salary.

Let's try to answer the following questions:

  • Are the professor ratings between different departments statistically different?
  • Is there a linear relationship between professor's salaries and their ratings on planetterp.com?

Are the professor ratings between different departments statistically different?¶

If you were to recall, we graphed professors' average ratings by department, and some departments turned out to have higher average ratings than others in our data. The median professor rating for ARHU-School of Languages, Literaures, and Cultures is 4.143, while the median for DO&IT is 2.357. But is this enough basis to claim that these departments truly have different average professor ratings? Or is it simply due to sampling error?

We have several independent samples of data (one for each department), and we would like to determine if they have the same average. This is a helpful flowchart that can help you decide on which hypothesis test you should use. The most common test for this kind of analysis is the analysis of variance (ANOVA) test, however, our data does not meet some of the assumptions required to use this test. One of the assumptions is that all of the samples follow a normal distribution. This does not hold true for our data. We already have a violin plot, but to confirm this, we can use histograms.

In [ ]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize=(12,12))
fig.tight_layout(pad=3)

# For each plot, graph the distribution of average ratings for professors by department
for i in range(4):
  for j in range(4):
    sns.histplot(data=merged_df_prof_large[(merged_df_prof_large['num_reviews'] > 2) & (merged_df_prof_large['department']==departments_pt[i*4+j])], x="average_rating", ax=axes[i][j])
    axes[i][j].set_title(departments_pt[i*4 + j][:30])
    axes[i][j].set_xlabel("Average Rating")

fig.suptitle("Distribution of Professors' Ratings by Department", y=1.02, fontsize=14)
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.02, "Distribution of Professors' Ratings by Department")

The plots above shows the distribution of professors' average ratings for each of the major departments. Notice that not many of them are normally distributed; the distributions somestimes appear uniform, bimodal, and/or right-skewed. They do not look normal, nor do we have a large enough sample size per sample to rely on the central limit theorem, so it would be ill-advised to perform an ANOVA test. Instead, we can do the non-parametric version of it: the Kruskal-Wallis Test. There are 4 assumptions that need to be checked in order to use this test accurately:

  1. The dependent variable is ordinal or continuous - This is true because average rating can be any number from 1 to 5.
  2. The independent variable is a 2 or more independent categories - This is true because our independent variable is departments, which are independent of each other because they are separate facilities in UMD. We also have much more than 2 departments in UMD.
  3. The observations are independent - This is true because it would not make sense for the rating of one professor to affect the rating of another professor unless there were very unusual circumstances.
  4. If the samples are similarly distributed, we can test the medians of the samples. Otherwise, the Kruskal-Wallis test will primarily be a test of dominance - As seen in the histograms above, the departments do not have similarly shaped distributions, so it would have to be the latter.

A test of dominance will test whether there exists a group such that its values tend to be higher than other groups by probability. If you want to learn more, check out stochastic dominance (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_dominance).

  • Null hypothesis: There exists no such group.
  • Alternative hypothesis: There exists such a group.

We will use 0.05 as our level of significance for all our hypothesis tests.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import kruskal

# Getting all the departments in one array
grouped_ratings = []
for department in departments_pt:
  grouped_ratings.append(merged_df_prof_large[(merged_df_prof_large['num_reviews'] > 2) & (merged_df_prof_large['department'] == department)]['average_rating'])

# Running the Kruskal-Wallis test
kruskal(*grouped_ratings)
Out[ ]:
KruskalResult(statistic=30.76761845183882, pvalue=0.009435509707798863)

The p-value is 0.00944, which is less than 0.05. This means that we have enough evidence to conclude that there is a department that tends to get higher ratings than another. How do we find out which department this is? We can run a post hoc test.

We can run the Dunn test, which typically follows a Kruskal-Wallis test. It performs multiple comparisons between all possible pairs of samples, and tells us which groups are different from each other. Read more about the Dunn test here.

Notice that the lowest p-value in the table generated by running the Dunn Test is between samples 4 and 5. These correlate to DO&IT and ARHU-School of Languages, Literatures, and Cultures respectively. This is not suprising because if we were to re-visit the violin plot of professors' ratings by department, DO&IT had the lowest median ratings, while the School of Languages, Literatures, and Cultures had one of the highest. However, the p-value is still only 0.090482, which is not less than 0.05. None of the p-values are low enough, but it doesn't exactly mean that these results should be ignored. This test may simply not be powerful enough. The Dunn test is known to be a bit more conservative to reduce errors, and pair that with the fact that it was run with 16 categories with small sample sizes, it is not surprising that the p-values are so high. For now, we cannot conclude that these two departments are different from each other with high confidence, but it is likely. We will need more data to confirm this.

Is there a linear relationship between professor's salaries and their ratings on planetterp.com?¶

It would be interesting to see whether or not a professor's rating is correlated to their salary. Are 'good' professors well-compensated? How about vice-versa? This could spur on many other potential questions, such as, are teachers more motivated with a higher salary? Of course, such questions are out of scope with the current data and level of statistical analysis we are doing, but it poses potential for future investigations if there is indeed a correlation. For now, I will be only looking at 2022 data because inflation over time could affect how we see salaries.

Interestingly enough, there is no correlation at all between salary and professor's ratings on planetterp.com. As seen in the results, there is a p-value associated with the independent variable 'average_rating.' This p-value represents the likelihood that the coefficient for this variable is 0. The null hypothesis is that the coefficient is equal to 0; the alternative hypothesis is that this coefficient is different from 0. Since it is a very high p-value (0.433), there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. In otherwords, we cannot claim that the coefficient is different from 0, and if that is the case, there is essentially no linear relationship between salary and average rating. This conclusion can also be reached by looking at the R-squared value, which is 0.002. This means that 0.2% of the variation in salary can be explained by average rating, which is a very low proportion.

Could there possibly be a linear relationship between rating and salary within a department? Unfortunately, there are not enough data points within most departments to run a linear regression analysis. To counter that, I will group by schools instead. As seen in previous graphs, schools tend to have similar distributions within them. We will only focus on three schools for now:

  • ARHU (Arts and Humanities)
  • BMGT (Business and Management)
  • CMNS (Computer, Mathematical, and Natural Sciences)

ARHU and BMGT were selected because they repeatedly showed up throughout the analysis, and CMNS was added along beause it is one of the biggest schools in UMD.

Conclusions¶

I pulled data from both planetterp.com and the Diamondback newspaper to extract various data about professors, including students' opinions on them as well as their university salary. I analyzed the data individually and then finally pieced them together to investigate whether there is a relationship between salary and ratings. The process required a lot of manipulation of the data to reduce the noise and to fill in empty rows. For example, some professors in the planetterp.com database only taught during past years, so their department and salary had to be extracted from older data. Another challenge was that the Diamondback contains salary data for all faculty members, meanwhile planetterp.com contains data on all instructors. It would be unfair to compare a professor to a lecturer due to their different responsibilities and expected componesation, so I tried to control for this by reducing the scope to focus on those with the 'Professor' titleship. The planetterp.com data also needed to be treated with caution because some faculty members would only have 1 or 2 anonymous review(s) under their name. With so few reviews, it is easy to get biased results, so such data entries were excluded from the analysis.

In the end, I managed to answer several questions:

What does the distribution of planetterp.com ratings look like?¶

On the planetterp.com website, there are an inflated number of 5 star ratings such that the median rating is 4.1. If you were to account for only professors, this drops down to 3.84, and if you were to filter out professors with only 1 or 2 reviews, this leaves us with a median of 3.67. Generally, the distribution is left-skewed. There are more professors with high ratings than lower ratings, but there is still a significant number who have an average rating of 2 or below.

How do the distribution of ratings differ by department?¶

I selected to only view the departments which had more than 10 professors with ratings. There were no two department which were exactly alike in their distribution. Some tended to have very high ratings such as ARHU , while some had low like DO&IT. Some departments had a lot of variation, some had very little. If we were to look at the schools however, there were some observable patterns. The ARHU school tends to have higher ratings, while the CMNS school tends to have departments right at the average with a very wide distribution.

Two particular departments stood out: BMGT-Decision, Operations & Information Technologies and ARHU-School of Languages, Literatures, and Cultures. After running a few statistical tests, these were picked out to be most likely different from each other, but there is still not enough data to confidently say it. In the future, it may be in UMD's interest to particularly pick out why so many professors in the BMGT school are suffering from low ratings on planetterp.com. Perhaps this will give some insight on hiring priorities or curricumulum structure.

What does the distribution of salaries look like?¶

The distribution for all UMD faculty is extremely right-skewed, similar to a power law distribution. It comes as no surprise that the president and the head sport coaches are some of the highest paid individuals in the university. For professors, the distribution is much more symmetrical, with a median salary of \$155,692.77. There is still an interquartile range of \$91,224.15, which is quite large.

What does the distribution of salaries look like by department?¶

I selected to view only departments with more than 17 professors. Similarly, many of the departments had diffferent averages and spread. Interestingly, DO&IT, which have some of the lower professor ratings, has a higher median salary than any of the other departments. Meanwhile, the ARHU schools tend to have higher professor ratings but earn below average salaries. Not to mention, the ARHU had the least variation in salary compared to other departments.

Is there a linear relationship between salary and planetterp.com rating?¶

It may wishful thinking that perhaps good professors are compensated with higher salaries, or perhaps higher salaries could inspire professors to meet students' expectations. Regardless of these what-if's, they beg of question of whether there is any correlation between salary and professor rating, and the answer is no. The p-value for the linear regression slope coefficient is too large to conclude that there is a significant relationship. The results are the same whether we look at all the data or separate it out by school.

It is unfortunate that 'good' professors are not rewarded with compensation that reflects their ability to teach. It would be interesting to experiment whether money could provide a strong enough incentive to improve their reviews.

In the future, more analysis can be done on the data that has not been touched at all in this tutorial. For the sake of remaining consistent, I only focused on professors, but it is hardly the truth that everyone who teaches a class is a professor. Many are lecturers, associate professors, assistant professors, emeritus professors, etc. A thorough analysis that takes titles into consideration could potentially open up more speculation on how we can restructure the education at UMD.
